 England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Chickering","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: unexplained. The surname seems to have died out in the British Isles.","History: The Chickering(e)s or Chickring(e)s who were in Dedham, MA, by <i>c.</i> 1670 were originally from Wrentham, Suffolk. However, only four Chickerings (all in Staffordshire) and one Chickring (from Devon) were recorded in the 1881 British census."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":7,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705197,"age":80,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Sir William Chickering was born about 1375, in Norfolk, England. He had at least 1 son with Lady William Chickering."},"et":{"about 1375–":"umbes 1375–Surnud","1365–Female":"1365–Surnud","1402–1438":"1402–1438","1375–Male":"1375–Surnud","1402":"1402","1455":"1455","1365":"1365","1375":"1375","1382":"1382","about 1375":"umbes 1375","1438":"1438","Wymondham, Norfolk, England":"Wymondham, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"about 1375–":"noin 1375–Kuollut","1365–Female":"1365–Kuollut","1402–1438":"1402–1438","1375–Male":"1375–Kuollut","1402":"1402","1455":"1455","1365":"1365","1375":"1375","1382":"1382","about 1375":"noin 1375","1438":"1438","Wymondham, Norfolk, England":"Wymondham, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England"},"fr":{"about 1375–":"environ 1375–Décédé","1365–Female":"1365–Décédée","1402–1438":"1402–1438","1375–Male":"1375–Décédé","1402":"1402","1455":"1455","1365":"1365","1375":"1375","1382":"1382","about 1375":"environ 1375","1438":"1438","Wymondham, Norfolk, England":"Wymondham, Norfolk, Angleterre","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Sir William Chickering est né environ 1375, à Norfolk, Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Lady William Chickering."},"de":{"about 1375–":"um 1375–Verstorben","1365–Female":"1365–Verstorben","1402–1438":"1402–1438","1375–Male":"1375–Verstorben","1402":"1402","1455":"1455","1365":"1365","1375":"1375","1382":"1382","about 1375":"um 1375","1438":"1438","Wymondham, Norfolk, England":"Wymondham, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","lifeSummary":"Sir William Chickering wurde um 1375 in Norfolk, England geboren. Er hatte mit Lady William Chickering minde